about: Raina Sokolov Gonzalez is a singer-songwriter and guitarist based in New York City. She is known for her unique blend of folk, rock, and indie pop. She has released two albums, 'Give it a Try' and 'Star to Light', and has toured extensively throughout the United States and Europe.

Lilly Gitlitz was born and raised in the endless summer of South Florida. Her music is vivid, introspective, and raw, abridging folk rock and indie pop styles. Distinctive, interweaving harmonies and narrative storytelling unite her songs. Lilly went to Wesleyan University where she was an active part of the school’s colorful, DIY music scene. After graduating in 2023, she moved to NYC and has been performing her original music alongside dear friends and collaborators. She’s joined by Audrey Mills and Cassidy McDonough, whose voices bring her songs to life.

Wolf van Elfmand is a songwriter, producer, and multi-instrumentalist. Raised in Western Colorado, his music explores genres under the vast umbrella term "Americana". Like many who trade in music, Wolf's story is not entirely built on themes of a bygone America. His compositions and life story reflect something tailor-made and of no other time than now. His work is a product of a good sense of humor, a good heart, and his ability to ignore the omnipresent whispers from life asking him to be still. To date, Wolf has provided support for Pokey LaFarge, Willie Watson, Turnpike Troubadours, Charlie Parr, Karl Blau, Wayne Hancock, and many, many others. He’s performed at prominent roots festivals, including Salmonfest (Alaska), The UMS (Denver), Midwest Music Fest (Wisconsin), and Brooklyn Folk Festival (New York). Wolf is based in Queens, New York, and is actively writing and performing. New releases are in the pipeline.

When his career as a student athlete didn't go as planned, Pook Hustle found new excitement pursuing his interest in writing. It was on this new playing field where his captivating energy paired with a smoky voice would shine through and garner the attention of those around him. The Brooklyn born Hip-Hop extraordinaire reminds us the nuances of the black experience.
Captain Tallen & the Benevolent Entities are tender storytellers, weaving lyrics that sing of nostalgia and yearning with delicate and thoughtful instrumentation. They are also a pirate ship.

Julián, a Brooklyn based guitarist and singer defined by their ethereal songwriting, has a new project that will reach for the depths of your heart and rock you to your core. Julián sites various influences that have led them to this point in their creative journey including the freedom and imagination of the Jimi Hendrix Experience and the John Coltrane Quartet as well as the tender songwriting and unique storytelling abilities of The Beatles and Milton Nascimento.

Mary Hood is an indie folk rock band comprised of singer/songwriter Mary Hood, bassist Brian Hart, drummer Billy Coughlin, and lead guitarist Griffin Jennings. Known for their ethereal sound, raw lyrics, and powerful dynamics, the band’s musical bond is undeniable. They draw influence from Radiohead, Elliott Smith, Fiona Apple, Big Thief, and early punk rock.

Caleb Jenson is a folk singer/songwriter briefly emerging from his musical hibernation to share a few personal tunes, echoing the likes of Adrianne Lenker, Andy Shauf, and James Taylor. His writing generally muses on the grief and vertigo of identity loss, and the struggle to find meaning in an otherwise ineffable reality. Or, he’s just singing about making coffee. Up to you.
